      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The distinction is between laws that regulate public safety and those that infringe upon conscience. Universal laws are necessary for societal function, but they cannot be absolute when they mandate actions that violate fundamental human dignity. Allowing exceptions for conscience is not cherry-picking; it is recognizing that a truly free society must protect the individual from the tyranny of the majority, even when that majority is codified in law.",
      "source": "target",
